The above graphs are representation of time series from 8 different classifiers. For this purpose, accelaration matrix are formed by cumulatively summing the accelaration data. Red graphs are accelaration data in 3D. Next to that, black graphs are the direct representation of the given data. I guess comparing both of them manually gives a better understanding of the classifier.

Secondly, k-NN method with 10-cross fold validation is used to train a model with two different distance measures. For this purpose, Euclidean and Manhattan distances have been used. Train function from the caret package is used for both distances. Finally, the error values for different ks are observed. Euclidean distance resulted in k=5 and Manhattan distance resulted in k=7.

#series (inefficient)

distMatrix=dist(combined)
print(str(distMatrix)) #it is distance matrix where first row (or column) has the distances we need
##  'dist' num [1:5050] 9.75 10.86 9.49 10.55 2.03 ...
##  - attr(*, "Size")= int 101

##  - attr(*, "Upper")= logi FALSE
##  - attr(*, "method")= chr "euclidean"
##  - attr(*, "call")= language dist(x = combined)
## NULL
#let's convert it to a regular matrix

neighborhood=order(distMatrix[1,]) #first array entry is 1, why?

#1-NN

For the ECG data, penalized fused lasso is performed. In order to do so, optL1 function in penalized package is used. For performing fused lasso training class data should be 1/0 matrix. Therefore, -1s in the class are converted to 0 whereas 1s remained as they are. Next, logistic regression is applied and coefficients and classes are observed in graphs. Coefficients flactuate between -1.5 and 1.5
